    "Lloyd R. Bailey": "). It thus is\nfar removed from evidencing the vengeance and cruelty with which\nsome modern interpreters have branded it.\nAt this point, one can come to a clearer understanding of why vv.\n15-16 (and the regulations that follow) have been placed here. The `[object_Tabernacle_Heb_9]`\noffender (vv. 10-11), by cursing the Deity, has in effect wished that\nGod were dead. Therefore in view of the more extensive lex talionis\nv. 22: let loose wild animals\nv. 22: make you few in number\nopens with reminders of the three of the Commandments: rever-\nence of parents, observance of the sabbath, and forbidding the\nproduction of idols. Why these in particular? Perhaps because, in\nthe articulation of the Commandments themselves (Exod 20 and\nDeut 5) the sanctions in case of these violation are singled out as\nespecially heavy (\u201cpunishing children for the iniquity of parents, to\nthe third and fourth generation . . . so that your days may be long\nin the land\u201d). Perhaps, then, it is upon careful observance of these\nCommandments that the future of the nation depends in large\nmeasure.\nPotential Blessings and Curses, 26:3-39\nA list of blessings\u201d and \u201ccurses\u201d (vv. 3-39) is the traditional conclu-\nsion to a covenant ceremony. The list here, forming a conclusion to\nthe entirety of chapters 17\u201325 (and de facto to the entire book of\nLeviticus), may be compared with Deuteronomy 27\u201328 (that like-\nwise conclude the legislative core consisting of chapters 12\u201326).\nParallels may also be found outside the Bible in a number of secular\ntreaty agreements that conclude in a similar fashion. [Extrabiblical\nBlessings and Curses]\nThe fifth set of curses (vv. 27-39, following vv. 16-17, 18-20, 21-\n22, and 23-26) is the most terrible of all. It features threats of\ncannibalism (",
