  "31": {
    "John Trapp": "I am the Lord your God. ] What need you then run to the devil for direction? Is it because there is no God in Israel? Every one that consults with Satan, worships him, though he bow not: neither doth that evil spirit desire any other reverence than to be sought unto.\nVer.\n31. I am the Lord your God.] What need you then run to the devil for direction? Is it because there is no God in Israel? Every one that consults with Satan, worships him, though he bow not: neither doth that evil spirit desire any other reverence than to be sought unto.\nVer.",
    "Lloyd R. Bailey": "225\n[v_Lev_18_1] Leviticus 18:1\u201320:27\nComment on Details of Leviticus 18\nv. 31). [Items Devoted for Destruction]\n[Comment on Details of Leviticus 27]\n322\n[v_Lev_27_1] [v_Lev_27_2] [v_Lev_27_3] [v_Lev_27_4] [v_Lev_27_5] [v_Lev_27_6] [v_Lev_27_7] [v_Lev_27_8] [v_Lev_27_9] [v_Lev_27_10] [v_Lev_27_11] [v_Lev_27_12] [v_Lev_27_13] [v_Lev_27_14] [v_Lev_27_15] [v_Lev_27_16] [v_Lev_27_17] [v_Lev_27_18] [v_Lev_27_19] [v_Lev_27_20] [v_Lev_27_21] [v_Lev_27_22] [v_Lev_27_23] [v_Lev_27_24] [v_Lev_27_25] [v_Lev_27_26] [v_Lev_27_27] [v_Lev_27_28] [v_Lev_27_29] [v_Lev_27_30] [v_Lev_27_31] [v_Lev_27_32] [v_Lev_27_33] [v_Lev_27_34] Leviticus 27:1-34\nPlowing and sowing a field in grain\nPlowing and sowing. 1st half 3rd C. AD. Roman mosaic from Saint Romain-en-Gal. Musee des\nAntiquites Nationales, Saint-Germain-en-Laye, France. (Photo Credit: Erich Lessing / Art\nResource, NY)\nConnections\nVows\nThe chapter is remarkable for its perceptions of human nature. It\nrealizes that, in moments of crisis, even the ardent sinner may \u201cget\nreligious\u201d and make promises to God; then,\nwhen the crisis is past, the person may seek to\nbe more \u201creasonable\u201d as to the depth of dedica-\ntion. One might say, for example: \u201cWell, one\nsacrificial act is about as good as another as far\nas God is concerned, so why not allow substitu-\ntions (to the human advantage, of course)? After\nall, the sentiment is the thing!\u201d There will thus\nbe quibbles about evaluation of the item\npledged, and attempts made to effect double-\nduty! Nonetheless, while recognizing this reality\nof human nature, the priests believed that self-\nserving (hence sinful) human nature could be\nguided toward integrity in the service of God,\nand apparently the community gave them the\nauthority to regulate such delicate matters.\nModern clergy will recognize many of their\nflock, and perhaps themselves, in these portraits\nof their spiritual ancestors. Their power to guide, however, may be\nfar less than that of their clerical predecessors. It will depend, in\npart, upon how well they have enabled the congregation to take\nScripture, Church, and the Christian life seriously. Their own\nauthority may rise and fall accordingly.\nStudy of this chapter might begin with reflec-\ntions\nupon\nthe\nimportance\nof\nthe\nchurch/Synagogue in the life of the larger com-\nmunity. This might involve a backward glance\nat some of the socio-economic guidelines in pre-\nvious chapters, building toward a portrait of the\nreligious community as an alternative to the\nindividuality, selfishness, injustice, and violence\nthat is everywhere evident in contemporary\nsociety. Where is hope for a different future to\nbe found? Only in the influence and triumph of\nthe People of God! However, such a community\ncannot be sustained by sporadic attendance at\nworship, undisciplined living, and fluctuating\n323\n[v_Lev_27_1] [v_Lev_27_2] [v_Lev_27_3] [v_Lev_27_4] [v_Lev_27_5] [v_Lev_27_6] [v_Lev_27_7] [v_Lev_27_8] [v_Lev_27_9] [v_Lev_27_10] [v_Lev_27_11] [v_Lev_27_12] [v_Lev_27_13] [v_Lev_27_14] [v_Lev_27_15] [v_Lev_27_16] [v_Lev_27_17] [v_Lev_27_18] [v_Lev_27_19] [v_Lev_27_20] [v_Lev_27_21] [v_Lev_27_22] [v_Lev_27_23] [v_Lev_27_24] [v_Lev_27_25] [v_Lev_27_26] [v_Lev_27_27] [v_Lev_27_28] [v_Lev_27_29] [v_Lev_27_30] [v_Lev_27_31] [v_Lev_27_32] [v_Lev_27_33] [v_Lev_27_34] Leviticus 27:1-34\nItems Devoted for Destruction\nThe inclusion of human beings in this\ncategory goes back to an ancient prac-\ntice in warfare. Ancient military leaders, in their\ndesire for divine assistance, would pledge to\ndestroy a city (sometimes including the entirety of\nits inhabitants, animals, and personal property). In\nthis fashion, there could be no motive for plunder,\nno personal gain, in an act of total dedication to\nGod. Evidence of this practice is to be found\nthroughout the ancient Near East, including\nIsrael\u2019s early traditions of conquest (e.g., the\n[v_Num_21_1] [v_Num_21_2] [v_Num_21_3] cities of Arad `[place_Arad_Num_21]` at Num 21:1-3 and, in modified\n[v_Jos_6_15] [v_Jos_6_16] [v_Jos_6_17] [v_Jos_6_18] [v_Jos_6_19] [v_Jos_6_20] [v_Jos_6_21] fashion, Jericho at Josh 6:15-21). Here, in H, it is\nmore traditional rhetoric than a driving desire for\nactualization.\nAncient Mathematics\nBoth the early Babylonians and\nEgyptians mastered the art of calcu-\nlating the area of such geometric shapes as\ntriangles, trapezoids, and rectangles, and beyond\nthat to the calculation of simple volumes (e.g., of\na truncated pyramid). Such calculation was not\ndone in the abstract (\u201cjust for the fun of it,\u201d as the\nlater Greeks would have done), but rather in the\nservice of practicality. A typical example, from the\nNew Kingdom Period of Egypt concerns a request\nmade of a Royal Scribe: \u201cA (building-) ramp is to\nbe constructed, 730 cubits long, 55 cubits wide\n. . . 60 cubits high at its summit, 30 cubits in the\nmiddle . . . Do not let it be said of you that there\nare things that even you do not know. Answer us\nhow many bricks are needed for it?\u201d (From O.\nNeugebauer, The Exact Sciences In Antiquity\n[New York: Harper Torchbooks, 1962], 79.)\nsupport. If it is a community worthy of membership, then it is a\ncommunity worthy of support (time and finances): one must not\nmake pledges, upon which others also depend, and then renege. A\npledge to the financial support of the church or synagogue is of\nwider and more enduring consequence than one to the loan officer\nor bank or department store. However, the former is passive about\nrequiring fulfillment whereas the latter will likely be coercive and\nthus one may feel free to neglect the former. Rare is the church\nmember who will even think of contrition concerning failure to\nkeep a pledge and then attempt to \u201cmake it up.\u201d God, the text\nseems to suggest, is a reality that members of the religious commu-\nnity should take at least as seriously as they take human\ninstitutions.\nAt the same time, modern congregational and denominational\nleaders must earn the kind of respect and trust that the priests in\nancient Israel apparently were accorded (in setting evaluations,\netc.). Such trust is undermined when modern leaders evidence\narrogant attitudes in accountability, accept excessive salaries, and\n\u201csell out\u201d traditional values in the pursuit of current (and often\nsecular) trends. Sometimes, withholding financial support is the\nonly weapon that the congregation has! Notice should also be made\n(although it is hardly grist for a sermon!) of the fact that Israel\u2019s\nsanctuary treasury could not participate in the acquisition of huge\nestates. This was in contrast to practice both among the neigh-\nboring states (Egypt and Babylonia in particular) and to some\nbranches of the medieval and modern church.\nNew Testament Connections\nVows, evidencing devotion to God and requiring integrity in their\nfulfillment, passed over into early Christianity with only slight\n324\n[v_Lev_27_1] [v_Lev_27_2] [v_Lev_27_3] [v_Lev_27_4] [v_Lev_27_5] [v_Lev_27_6] [v_Lev_27_7] [v_Lev_27_8] [v_Lev_27_9] [v_Lev_27_10] [v_Lev_27_11] [v_Lev_27_12] [v_Lev_27_13] [v_Lev_27_14] [v_Lev_27_15] [v_Lev_27_16] [v_Lev_27_17] [v_Lev_27_18] [v_Lev_27_19] [v_Lev_27_20] [v_Lev_27_21] [v_Lev_27_22] [v_Lev_27_23] [v_Lev_27_24] [v_Lev_27_25] [v_Lev_27_26] [v_Lev_27_27] [v_Lev_27_28] [v_Lev_27_29] [v_Lev_27_30] [v_Lev_27_31] [v_Lev_27_32] [v_Lev_27_33] [v_Lev_27_34] Leviticus 27:1-34\nComment on Details of Leviticus 27\n19:31\n493"
  },
