  "1": {
    "Lloyd R. Bailey": "18, 30-37; 20:3-6; 25:39-40 [probably 25:39-46 is meant]; 25:47-53; etc.\n8 For example, at 1:2; 4:2; 7:22, 28; 8:5; 11:2; 12:2; 15:1.\n9 For example, 6:8, 24; 8:31; 9:2, 7; 10:12; 13:1; 14:1, 33; 16:2.\n10 It does not, however, designate it as \u201cthe holy land\u201d as did later usage.\n11 Note 7:37-38 as a similar conclusion to chapters 1\u20137 and 16:34 as a conclusion\nv. 1 (\u201cSay\n224\n[v_Lev_18_1] Leviticus 18:1\u201320:27\nMasoretic Accents and Interpretation\nThe Masoretes, in adding accent marks (to locate the \u201cstress\u201d on each word), also exer-\ncised judgment in the process of interpretation. Here, the text speaks of the expulsion of\nthe Canaanites because of their defilement of the land. The Masoretic Text accents the word\n\u201cvomit\u201d as a participle, indicating an action that is in process (or on the verge of) happening: \u201cas it\nis [even now] vomiting out the nation that was before you.\u201d Thereby the text is made to speak\nfrom the perspective of Israel, still at Mt. Sinai, anticipating moving on to the \u201cpromised land.\u201d In\nactuality, however, the biblical writer recorded this material centuries later than the event and\ntherefore may well have intended the accent to be located in such a way as to indicate the past\ntense: hence NEB, \u201cas it [has] vomited out . . .\u201d (so also NEB).\n[v_Lev_10_18] For other kinds of activity by the Masoretes, see the discussion of Lev 10:18; 11:23-24; and"
  }
